# Motivation {#motivation background-color="#2C7FB8"}

## PDE-constrained Inverse Problems
[**Aim:**]{.fg style="--col: #e64173"} Infer unknown parameters in PDE(s) given measurements of the solution of the PDE(s).


::: {.columns style="margin-bottom: 0;"}


::: {.column width="50%"}

::: {.callout-note style="margin-bottom: 0em;"}
## Forward Problem
Given $\red{\kappa(x)}$, $\red{f(x) }$ and $\red{p_0}$, find $\blue{p(x)}$ such that
$$
\begin{aligned}
- \nabla \!\cdot\! \big(\red{\kappa(x)}\color{black}{\nabla} \blue{p(x)} \big)&= \red{f(x) }
&& x\in \Omega, \\
\blue{p(x)} &= \red{p_0}
&&x\in \partial\Omega .
\end{aligned}
$$
:::

:::

::: {.column width="50%"}


::: callout-important
## Inverse Problem

Given $\blue{p(x)}$, find $\red{\kappa(x)}$, $\red{f(x) }$ and $\red{p_0}$ such that 
$$
\begin{aligned}
- \nabla \!\cdot\! \big(\red{\kappa(x)}\nabla \blue{p(x)} \big)&= \red{f(x) }
&& x\in \Omega, \\
\blue{p(x)} &= \red{p_0}
&&x\in \partial\Omega .
\end{aligned}
$$

:::
:::
:::

**Overarching Applications of Inverse Problems:** 

- Model calibration e.g. $\red{\kappa(x)}$, may be partially known (cannot be measured directly) or subject to [**uncertainty**]{.fg style="--col: #e64173"}. 

- Tomography: inference of physical properties e.g.$\red{\kappa(x)}$



