# Inversion Framework {#EKI background-color="#2C7FB8"}



## General framework {.scrollable}

**Forward Problem (FP)**:

$$
\left\{
\begin{aligned}
\textit{Model Equations (MEs):} &\quad \mathcal{M}(\red{u},\blue{p}) = 0 \\
\textit{Prediction of QoI:} &\quad \blue{d} = \mathcal{H}(\blue{p})
\end{aligned}
\right.
$$
**Forward Map:**  $\red{u}\xrightarrow{\;\;\mathcal{F}\;\;} \blue{d}=\mathcal{F}(\red{u})$

[**Inverse Problem (IP)**:]{.alert} 

Find $\red{u^{\dagger}}$ (the truth) given  measurements, $\color{#0044cc}{d^{\eta}}$ of $d^{\dagger}=\mathcal{F}(\red{u^{\dagger}})$.

Common (modelling) assumption:
$$
\begin{align*}
\blue{d^{\eta}}&=\overbrace{\mathcal{F}(\red{u^{\dagger}})}^{d^{\dagger}}+\eta,\qquad \eta: measurement~noise
\end{align*}
$$

[**Classical approaches**]{.alert}

Least-squares:
$$
u^{\eta}=\argmin_{u\in U}~~\overbrace{ \norm{ \blue{d^{\eta}}-\mathcal{F}(\red{u})}^2}^{data~misfit}
$$

<details>
<summary>Ill-posedness</summary>

::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="50%"}

  - Lack of uniqueness 
  - Lack of stability 
    - small $\eta\Rightarrow u^{\eta}\not\to u^{\dagger}$

:::

::: {.column width="50%"}

![](Figs/cat.png){width=80%}

:::

:::

</details>


<details>
<summary>Addressing stability: Regularisation</summary>

- Regularise then Optimise e.g. Tikhonov

$$u^{\eta}=\argmin_{u\in U}~~\overbrace{ \norm{ \blue{d^{\eta}}-\mathcal{F}(\red{u})}^2}^{data~misfit}+\overbrace{\alpha\norm{ \red{u}}_{\mathcal{R}}^2}^{regularisation}$$ 

- Regurlise within the optimiser:

  - Iterarively-regularised Gauss-Newton
  - Landweber iteration
  - regularising Levenberg-Marquardt

</details>



Limitations of Regularisation:

- Does not address uniqueness

- Does not quantify uncertainty

- Requires derivative $D\cF$ (and its adjoint $D\cF^*$)

- Not straightforward to incorporate discontinuities of $\red{u(x)}$







[**Quantifying Uncertainty**:]{.alert} The Bayesian Approach

- Put a prior on $\red{u}$: $\mathbb{P}(\red{u})$. 

- Find the posterior

$$
\mathbb{P}(\red{u}\vert \blue{d^{\eta}})\propto \overbrace{\mathbb{P}(\red{u})}^{prior}\overbrace{\mathbb{P}(\blue{d^{\eta}}\vert \red{u})}^{likelihood}
$$

[**Challenges**:]{.alert}


- In general $\mathbb{P}(\red{u}\vert \blue{d^{\eta}})$ does not admit closed-form solution

- Sampling of $\mathbb{P}(\red{u}\vert \blue{d^{\eta}})$ (e.g. via MCMC) is computationally unfeasible.

  - Recall $\red{u}$ is a function (i.e. high-dimensional after discretisation). 

- How to incorporate discontinuities of $\red{u}$.

## Ensemble Kalman Inversion (EKI)  {.scrollable}



Assumption $\blue{d^{\eta}}=\mathcal{F}(\red{u^{\dagger}})+\eta,\qquad \eta\sim N(0,\Gamma)$

Hence posterior:
$$
\mathbb{P}(\red{u}\vert \blue{d^{\eta}})\propto \mathbb{P}(\red{u})\exp\Big[-\frac{1}{2}\norm{\Gamma^{-1/2}(\blue{d^{\eta}}-\mathcal{F}(\red{u}))}^2 \Big]
$$

[**Main idea:**]{.fg style="--col: #e64173"} Construct particle/sample approximations of internediate measures

$$\mathbb{P}(\red{u})=\mathbb{P}_{0}(\red{u})\mapsto \mathbb{P}_{1}(\red{u})\mapsto\dots \mathbb{P}_{N}(\red{u})=\mathbb{P}(\red{u}\vert \blue{d^{\eta}})$$

::: {.callout-tip}

## EKI Algorithm

Start with samples from the prior: $\{u^{(j)}\}_{j=1}^{J}$, $u^{(j)}\sim \mathbb{P}(u)$

For $n=0,\dots, N$:

- Compute $\cF^{(j)}:=\cF(u^{(j)})$
- Compute 
$$
\displaystyle\mathcal{C}^{\cF\cF} = \frac{1}{J-1}\sum_{j=1}^J\big(\cF^{(j)}- \bar{\cF}\big)\otimes\big(\cF^{(j)}-\bar{\cF}\big)\qquad 
  \displaystyle\mathcal{C}^{u\cF} = \frac{1}{J-1}\sum_{j=1}^J\big(u^{(j)} - \bar{u}\big)\otimes\big(\cF^{(j)}-\bar{\cF}\big)
  $$
  
  where $\displaystyle\bar{\cF} = \frac{1}{J}\sum_{j=1}^J \cF^{(j)}$ and $\displaystyle \bar{u} = \frac{1}{J}\sum_{j=1}^J u^{(j)}$\;

- Update each particles, at eah iteration:

$$
u^{(j)}\leftarrow u^{(j)}+C^{u\cF}(C^{\cF \cF} +\alpha_{n}\Gamma  )^{-1}(d^{\eta}+\sqrt{\alpha_n}\xi-\cF(u^{(j)}))$$
where $\xi\sim N(0,\Gamma)$ and $\alpha_{n}$ is a regularisation/tempering parameter. 

:::

- [**EKI is derivative/Jacobian free**]{.bg style="--col: #e64173"}.
- EKI is a heuristic approximate method
  - in general it does not provide samples of the exact posterior.



## Informal Derivation of EKI {.scrollable}
See [@Iglesias_2021]
<details>
  <summary>
  [**Tempering:**]{.alert} Build transitions between prior and posterior     
$$\mathbb{P}(\red{u})=\mathbb{P}_{0}(\red{u})\mapsto \mathbb{P}_{1}(\red{u})\mapsto\dots \mathbb{P}_{N}(\red{u})=\mathbb{P}(\red{u}\vert \blue{d^{\eta}})$$
  </summary>
  Define
  $$\mathbb{P}_{n}(\red{u})\propto \mathbb{P}(\red{u})\exp\Big[-\frac{\xi_{n}}{2}\norm{\Gamma^{-1/2}(\blue{d^{\eta}}-\mathcal{F}(\red{u}))}^2 \Big]$$
  with $0= \xi_{0}<\xi_{1}<\dots<\xi_{N+1}=1$.
  Then write recursively:
  $$\mathbb{P}_{n+1}(\red{u})\propto \mathbb{P}_{n}(\red{u})\exp\Big[-\frac{1}{2}\norm{(\alpha_{n}\Gamma)^{-1/2}(\blue{d^{\eta}}-\mathcal{F}(\red{u}))}^2 \Big]$$
  where $\alpha_{n}=(\xi_{n+1}-\xi_{n})^{-1}$
  
</details>

<details>
  <summary> Linearise $\mathcal{F}(\red{u})$ around the mean of $\mathbb{P}_{n}(\red{u})$.
</summary>

  $$\mathbb{P}_{n+1}(\red{u})\propto \mathbb{P}_{n}(\red{u})\exp\Big[-\frac{1}{2}\norm{(\alpha_{n}\Gamma)^{-1/2}(\blue{d^{\eta}}-\mathcal{F}(m_{n})-D\mathcal{F}(m_{n})(\red{u}-m_n))}^2 \Big]$$
</details>


<details>
  <summary> Gaussianise $\mathbb{P}_{n}(\red{u})\approx N(m_{n},C_{n})$ so the linearised problem is solved in closed form for the Gaussian $\mathbb{P}_{n+1}(\red{u})=N(m_{n+1}, C_{n+1})$
</summary>
$$
\begin{aligned}
m_{n+1}=&m_{n}+C_{n}D\cF_n^{*}(D\cF_nC_{n}\,D\cF_n^{*} +\alpha_{n}\Gamma   )^{-1}(d^{\eta}-\cF_n)\\
C_{n+1}=&C_{n}-C_{n}D\cF_n^{*}(D\cF_nC_{n}\,D\cF_n^{*} +\alpha_{n}\Gamma   )^{-1}D\cF_nC_{n}
\end{aligned}
$$
where $\cF_{n}=D\cF(m_{n})$
</details>


<details>
  <summary> Approximate derivatives with covariances 
  </summary>
  If $u_{n}\sim N(m_{n},C_{n})$, then  
$$
\begin{aligned}
\E[\cF(u_{n})] \simeq &\cF_n \\
\co[\cF(u_{n})] \simeq   &D\cF_nC_{n}D\cF_n^{*},\\
\co[u_{n},\cF(u_{n})] \simeq  & C_{n}D\cF_n^{*}.
\end{aligned}
$$

Hence
$$
\begin{aligned}
m_{n+1}\simeq &m_{n}+\red{\co[u_{n},\cF(u_{n})]}(\red{\co[\cF(u_{n})]}+\alpha_{n}\Gamma   )^{-1}(d^{\eta}-\red{\E_{n}[\cF(u_{n})]})\\
C_{n+1}\simeq &C_{n}-\red{\co[u_{n},\cF(u_{n})]}(\red{\co[\cF(u_{n})]}+\alpha_{n}\Gamma   )^{-1}\red{\co[\cF(u_{n}),u_{n}]}
\end{aligned}
$$
</details>

<details>
  <summary> Use sample approximations of expectations/covariances 
  </summary>
$$\mathbb{P}_{n}(u_n)\simeq \mathbb{P}_{n}^{J}(u_n):=\frac{1}{J}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\delta_{u_{n}^{(j)}},\qquad u_{n}^{(j)}\sim\mathbb{P}_{n}(u_n)=N(m_{n},\mathcal{C}_{n})$$
$$u_{n+1}^{(j)}=u_{n}^{(j)}+C_{n}^{u\cF}(C_{n}^{\cF \cF} +\alpha_{n}\Gamma  )^{-1}(d^{\eta}+\sqrt{\alpha_n}\xi_{n}^{(j)}-\cF(u_{n}^{(j)}))$$
where $\xi_{n}^{(j)}\sim N(0,I)$ and $C_{n}^{u\cF}$ and $C_{n}^{\cF\cF}$ are the sample approximations of $\red{\co[u_{n},\cF(u_{n})]}$ and $\red{\co[\cF(u_{n})]}$, respectively 
</details>


