## Magnetic Resonance Elastography {#app-mre .scrollable}


[**Aim:**]{.fg style="--col: #e64173"} Remote palpation by shear waves, i.e. tomographic quantification of shear modulus of biological tissue.




::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="60%"}

- Induce excitation at a given frequency (e.g. 50Hz).


- Measure (complex) displacements $\blue{\bfu(\bfx)}$ via MRI (Motion encoding gradient).



- Invert displacements to find 
shear modulus $\red{G(\bfx)}$: viscoelastic properties

:::

::: {.column width="40%"}


![](Figs_for_MRE/Set1.png){width=95%}





:::

:::



::: {#fig-mre-workflow}
![](Figs_for_MRE/Set2.png){width=100%}

A: T1/T2 weighted B: $\vert \bfu(\bfx)\vert$ C: $\vert G(\bfx)\vert\qquad$.^[Images from: Tan CH, Venkatesh SK. *MRE and Other Magnetic Resonance Imaging Techniques in Chronic Liver Disease: Current Status and Future Directions.* Gut and Liver 2016;10:672–686.]
:::




## Forward/Inverse Problem in MRE {.scrollable}

::: callout-note

## Forward Model

Time-harmonic isotropic linear viscoelastic equations
$$
\rho \omega^2 \blue{\bfu} +\nabla \cdot \big[ \red{G} (\nabla \blue{\bfu} +(\nabla \blue{\bfu})^{T})\big]+\nabla (\red{\lambda} \nabla \cdot \blue{\bfu})=\mathbf{0},\qquad \text{in}~ \Omega,
$$
:::

- Known quantities:  $\omega$ (frequency) and $\rho\approx 10^{3}\text{kg}/\text{m}^3$.  

- Unknown quantities: BCs, $\red{\lambda(\bfx)}$ and $\red{G(\bfx)}$

- Measured quantities (via MRI):  $\blue{\bfu_{M}\equiv (\bfu(\bfx_{1}),\dots,\bfu(\bfx_{M}))}$



::: callout-important

## Inverse Problem

Find the shear modulus $\red{G(\bfx)=G_{s}(\bfx)+iG_{l}(\bfx)}$ given measurements of  $\blue{\bfu_{M}\equiv (\bfu(\bfx_{1}),\dots,\bfu(\bfx_{M}))}$.

:::

$\red{G_{s}(\bfx)}$: storage modulus. $\red{G_{l}(\bfx)}$: loss modulus. 


